SkyComment: This was probably the most stars I've ever seen in my whole life at once. The sky was perfectly clear, and it felt like you could see the entire universe. It seemed like the "left" side of the sky had more visible stars, but I honestly have no idea which cardinal direction "left" was. The stars were shining and twinkling brightly, and I could see more constellations than I've ever seen before.
LocationComment: This was a great dark sky location, at a hotel up the mountain of Telluride. There were just a few streetlights, and some light coming from the town of Telluride. But outside of those small items, I was in the middle of the mountains!

SkyComment: There were just a few clouds in the sky, but there was definitely some sort of haze that prevented optimal star viewing. The stars weren't really popping out at me like they typically do, and there just weren't that many visible stars to be completely honest. The region of the sky directly above and East of me had the most stars, and then outside of that there wasn't too much.
LocationComment: My bright site observing location was right in the middle of the Norlin Quad. This is definitely a bright site, (it's in the middle of a college campus) with plenty of nearby light pollution. There were a few nearby street lights that illuminated walkways, and of course all the lights from the hill are super close to the Quad.

SkyComment: Once again, there were no evidences of factors that accentuate the atmospheric extinction, such as haze, fog, smog or clouds. The observation was done after astronomical twilight and with the waning moon (phase = 0.11) near nadir. Other for a mild glow along the horizon, which could be attributed to light sources in nearby farms, the sky was absolutely pristine.
LocationComment: The observation site is a fairly unpopulated street between two of the main roads that serve the city. Street lighting is sparse and done primarily by sodium lamps, there is no sign of LED lights. The view of the western horizon is wide and unobstructed.

SkyComment: No signs of clouds, haze or skyglow. Observation was made after astronomical twilight and with the moon (phase angle = 0.11) below the horizon.
LocationComment: Urban location in the town's center, right next to the city council. When it comes to the main sources of public lighting, yellow-hued sodium lamps prevail in this street. Almost the entirety of the sky can be seen from this observation site, which offers a great view of constellations along the celestial equator and around the southern celestial pole.

SkyComment: AM- There was a fair amount of cloud cover, perhaps as much as 30%. These were fairly dense clouds where they did occur. However, the sky around Leo was clear and perfectly visible as the cloud cover was to the east of the constellation. I didn't notice any distinct sky glow during my observations.
LocationComment: AM- Rural location for observations. Definite tree line, although at some distance from the observer. Only lights were from a porch light several hundred feet away. Some definite dampness from earlier rain.

SkyComment: AM- There had been very heavy cloud cover the entire day. Over the course of the observation, the clouds broke somewhat, especially around Leo and Gemini. Most of the sky was heavily obscured in thick clouds though. There was a definite sky glow towards the North- Northeast. What areas of the sky were clear, however, had bright and observable stars.
LocationComment: AM- Observations made from a rural location. There was a noticeable perimeter of trees, however, the observer's location was in a large clearing. The air and ground were rather wet from rain. There was very minimal if any surrounding light.

SkyComment: AM- The sky tonight was almost entirely clear. Some very thin and wispy clouds in the North and East. There wasn't any distinct sky glow that I noticed. Once my eyes were adjusted I was able to see a great number of stars. Leo was clearly visible in the sky.
LocationComment: AM- Rural location. The perimeter of the observer location is densely treed, although the location itself is clear. There were minimal surrounding lights, only some porch lighting at a distance.

SkyComment: Sky was a little hazy and there was some was some ambient light pollution from neighbors landscape and patio lights. Some of these lights let light shine upward or to the sides. Northwest is bright from Phoenix light dome. This observation was made after the constellation passed its transit so it was in the southwest. Naked eye limiting magnitude was 4.Also, edit report #320470 -mag 4 is correct.
LocationComment: My viewing area is the back yard. The area is a rapidly growing area of San Tan Valley / Queen Creek within the Encanterra community. Neighbors on both sides use landscaping lights at night. Trees partially block some of the light. Occasional street traffic causes car lights to shine into my night sky viewing

Four streetlights line the road next to the field, but they are facing away from where my observations were made so they did not have a significant impact on my observations.
